text: Yeah. I mean, I think fundamental to the research process to building a systematic strategy is to articulate the mechanisms driving returns. And as you said, there are some overlaps between fixed income equity. But I think it's important to start with first principles and just uncover and unpick those mechanisms as far as possible. So, as I said, we do two areas here, corporate credit and rates. I think the closest relation to equities is corporate credit. And what drives a corporate bond price? Well, if we take out the rates element, which is what we do by default in all our modeling, then you're left with a credit spread. Now, you could say that credit spread is similar to the equity price in the sense that good news for the firm in terms of earnings or cash flows will have a positive impact on spread. It will narrow spreads and it will make the equity price rally. So, you could say, well, there are some strong similarities there. But looking in more detail, the corporate bond investor and the equity investor have different claims on the firm's assets. The corporate bond investor has much. More limited upside than the equity investor. And they get compensated for that limited upside by earning a spread. So, although some of the earnings information is common, the reaction to it need not be. They'll be in an asymmetry. Good news for the equity investor or for the equity will carry on being good news. And there's not really a limit to the upside there. Whereas in corporate bond terms, there's a limit to the upside in terms of, well, once the earnings picture is really good or the cash flow picture is really good, there's a limit to how much the spread can narrow. Because it's also driven by. There are things like liquidity premium. And there are also things like callability, which stop a bond's price rallying above or significantly above par. So, again, it's about articulating the mechanisms in detail that drive the asset's price. And that goes for signals, insights. And it also goes for any other component in the investment process that I described. So, risk models. I think valuation is a massive area. So, when we're thinking about valuation in equities. I guess we're thinking about. Some relatively simple price ratio based models on the fixed income side. It's very different. You've got to think about the risk of the firm, its leverage, how far it is from default, and then any one of a number of structural models that help you gauge what the fair spread is. So, again, it comes back to this thesis of a common framework in terms of thinking about signal categories, perhaps, but always the differences, the details being different. So, another area that I think is very important and very interesting to think about in terms of system. So, I think the first area that I think is very important is the action of the market participants. What do they do in terms of affecting corporate bond prices? So, there's a paper that we wrote called Reaching for Safety back in my BlackRock days. I wrote it with a guy called Johnny Kang who did most of the work. So, I should give him a hat tip. And there's a decent literature on this topic, actually, not just our paper. So, this paper explores the impact of ratings constrained investors on corporate bond pricing. So, if we take insurance companies, for example, which are some of the biggest holders of the market. So, if we take insurance companies, for example, which are some of the biggest holders of the market. They are typically constrained in terms of the exposure to lower rated names they can take. They face higher capital requirements, say, for taking on lower rated exposure. So, they tend to avoid lower rated bonds, but they also need yield. So, they want to own the higher yielding bonds within the decently rated groups. Now, why would some bonds in a given ratings group be higher yielding? It could be random, sure. But it's more likely that there is some extra risk for that name that the market needs to take. It has priced. And the consequence of that is a higher yield or a higher spread. But by focusing only on rating, the investor is ignoring that and saying, hey, I can get some carry. I can get some yield. So, the consequence of that investor ignoring any other measures of risk than rating, treating the ratings as a whole proxy for risk, is those bonds will be attractive. Their prices will get bid up and their spreads will be lower. And that means that these bonds, which should trade rider for a reason, will be rich. And the consequence of that is if you actually. Realize that dynamic holds, if you avoid those bonds, which will have lower risk adjusted returns, you can get some alpha in corporate bond space. So, I think that's just a nice example of a market structural effect where investors with ratings constraints that are motivated to get as much yield as possible or create a mispricing, which can be exploited by investors who realize the underlying mechanism. And I think fixed income is full of whether it be the rates area or the credit area of situations where the actions are one or other. Types of market participants will create alpha opportunities.
